      textEn: [
        "The white egret is an exquisite poem.",
        "The blending of colors, the proportions of its body \u2014 everything is just right. The white crane is too large and stiff; even the rosy ibis or grey heron seem a bit too big and too uncommon.",
        "Yet the white egret, because of how common it is, has had its beauty forgotten.",
        "That snow-white downy plumage, the streamlined form of its entire body, that iron-colored long beak, those blue-green feet \u2014 add a fraction and it would seem too long, subtract a fraction and it would seem too short, a shade lighter and it would seem too white, a shade darker and it would seem too black.",
        "In the clear paddy fields, one or two egrets stand fishing from time to time, and the whole field becomes a painting set in a glass frame. The size of the field seems as if designed by someone with the egret in mind.",
        "On clear mornings, one often sees it standing alone at the very top of a small tree, looking unsteady, yet it is perfectly at ease. This is a preference that other birds can hardly display. People say it is keeping watch, but is it really?",
        "Catching a glimpse of a white egret flying low in the evening sky is one of the blessings of country life. It is the embodiment of clarity, and it possesses life.",
        "Perhaps some feel it is a pity that the egret cannot sing. But isn\u2019t the egret itself a beautiful song?",
        "\u2014 No, a song would be too resounding.",
        "The white egret is truly a poem, a prose poem with rhythm deep in its bones."
      ],
