      textEn:[
        "It must have been a dream last night\u2014I\u2019ve just awakened! In the haze, Father and Mother got up at midnight to add mulberry leaves to the silkworms\u2026 Every year when it was time to sell cocoons, I would follow Father. After selling the cocoons, he would buy me loquats\u2026",
        "I saw Aunt\u2019s husband\u2019s little fishing boat again. Whenever Father sent me away from home for entrance exams or school, he would borrow that little boat. We brought rice to cook on board and slept on the boat at night to save on meals and lodging.",
        "Once, Father and I stayed at the cheapest little inn. I was woken at midnight by bedbugs, covered in big red welts. Father was heartbroken. Though I was young, I already deeply understood how hard it was for Father to earn money.",
        "In a daze, I found myself again at the biennial temple fair. Father and I were both hungry. How I craved the food! But I didn\u2019t dare, didn\u2019t have the heart to ask Father to buy any. Father had brought rice dumplings from home. We found a secluded spot and sat down to eat cold dumplings. After eating, Father felt I had been too deprived, so he took me to a stall for a bowl of hot tofu pudding.",
        "Father always told me to study hard and hopefully become a teacher someday. During primary school, on days of heavy rain or snow when the roads were slippery, Father would carry me on his back to school.",
        "When I graduated from lower primary, I passed the exam for Eshan Upper Primary. Money was tight, but the family was willing to spend it all on me. When Father brought me to school and made my bed, I secretly cried after he left. It was the first time I truly cried from heartache.",
        "I was going to take the entrance exam for Wuxi Normal School. To save on travel, Father again borrowed his brother-in-law\u2019s little fishing boat. Heaven doesn\u2019t fail those who try\u2014his son passed the exam. When he took me to enroll, it was still that same little boat. When Father wasn\u2019t rowing, he would use the time to mend my cotton quilt. Looking out from the cabin, his hunched figure sewing blocked my view.",
        "When will I ever be able to use the pen in my own hand to paint that little boat laden with a father\u2019s love!\u2026 I woke up, and the pillow was wet."
      ],
